>5th fret note = Open note of string below
>7th fret note = Open note of string above
>12 fret note = Open note of that string + 1 octave

>2 strings lower + 2 frets lower = Down one octave of note
>E# = F
>Fb = E
>B# = C
>Cb = B

posts.name: miyamoto usagi
posts.com:
>>114551477
this really,
I've mastered my own crap for a long time, and the key I've realized is: range compression, and a tiny bit of limiting. It will *look way amped out, but the sound is reallllly goood. Here's what I do: after all the sounds have good volume levels, and I've added the effects I wanna add, and the width, and the compression of certain tracks that need it. That's when I press mix and render, and then I take that mix and turn it into 5 tracks all playing at the same time (you can tell if the yellow line is there when you slide them that they are congruent.)

SO, the 5 tracks are: the mids, the highs, the lows, a version with saturation/reverb, and the original.
for the lows I do a low pass of 1000hz, normalize, maybe add a small bass boost, and then compress it, then normalize again,and maybe limit it if needed, and then normalize.
For the mids I do a high pass of 1000, normalize, do a low pass of 5000, normalize, add compression, normalize, then add limiter if needed, and normalize.(all of these are usually -0.1 db)
For the highs it's the same process except the difference is I do a highpass of 5000.
for the saturation/reverb track I add either saturation or distortion, then add reverb, then normalize.
and for the original I just normalize that and nothing else.
then I turn everything down the same rate, usually like, -5 to -7 db, and have a listen, then adjust if needed like if one of these needs to stand out more, then I click mix and render again, and then I normalize it to -.01, and it usually makes... a pretty nice sound.

What type of knob you have?
Is it Les Paul style or the ones like in stratos?

Well, since it's new that could be the reason for it's hard to turn for a while.

But also it's worth mentioning that Les Paul knobs requires more "effort" (or a larger motion with your hand) to go from 10 to 0 because it has a larger diameter compared to the Strato ones. So it can give the impression that it's "hard" do turn.

I play a SG for 10 years and I still get annoyed by the huge ass knob, it's like and endless motion with my little finger and when I think i reached 0 there is still a little bit more to mute the guitar completely.

You that is your case, you could try borrowing a Strato knob and switching it with yours just to see if it's more comfortable for you.

You're going at songwriting all wrong if you're worrying about tuning standards and stuff. And I really hate to say that, its art, go at it how you like, but don't get bogged down in such minutae; no two performances will be the same. Leave it where it is, figure out the rest of the song, and record that old part over it again when the time comes, the song will come out better for it. Focus more on feeling and context than perfection, even if you got, in a vacuum, what you think is the perfect take. Perfectionism is a habit you've gotta kick early if you want your stuff to stand out and feel "real" cliche as that sounds

>>114496636
These are their albums worth checking out

>Killing Technology
Proggy thrash metal
>Dimension Hatross
Thrashy prog metal, less emphasis on the thrash. Probably their proggiest album.
>Nothingface
Progressive metal with a pretty unique post-punk edge, not so much thrash metal
>The Outer Limits
Pretty solid prog metal with a clear early 90s alternative rock sound. Jack Luminous is their best song.
>The Wake
Surprisingly great return to form to their Dimension Hatross sound after 25 years of mediocrity

Their first two albums aren't prog.
Angel Rat's a weird alternative rock/metal album, some people like it but it's not prog.
Negatron is their obligatory 1990s 80s-thrash-metal-band-gone-butt-metal album but with Voivod's signature angular dissonant riffing style.
Phobos is Negatron but more spaced out and proggy, might be worth listening to if you don't mind 90s butt metal.

Literally everything Voivod's put out in the 2000s and early 2010s has been unremarkable until The Wake.

Retard. Ear fatigue objectively is a thing. If you rode a really scary roller coaster, it would be exciting the first time and the drops and loops etc. (i.e. dynamic changes, key changes, drops etc.) would make you feel scared/excited. After the 5th or 10th time it would no longer make you feel any emotions, and after that you'd just feel nothing or even frustration. If you gave it a break for like a month then came back, you might feel some of that emotion again, but you'd know exactly what to expect and that feeling would immediately go back to being "fatigue" after the first ride back.

This applies to everything in life, for every single human being. You are not special.

>>114544368
perhaps keep the writing for the parts simple

i do a lot of piano too, i was working on a song that began on keyboard, a simple 8 measures translated into my edm sound. i started by seperating the harmony part from the melody (you can think of this as rh/lh parts) and the bass too. i kinda just copy pasted whatever i had for the melody into the instrument i wanted to use for this, and did the same with the harmony. for the bass, i thought i could do a little more because it's not like when writing piano, you can press on the pedals like it's an organ and use the sustained bass. so with this in mind, i let myself have a little more freedom in exploring what i wanted out of the bass in context to the song, although i still kept it simple. i add in the drums by ear, and some percussion/sfx/upper register twinkle to top it off. then, i add in any plugins i want, any sound design tricks i had in mind, and just build off of what i have for the rest of the song.

my advice is pretty general, and does not entirely apply to you, but there are different ways to write for a part when translating it from piano to whatever to maximize not only the fullest potential of that instrument, but the song as a whole. it's really good to start thinking of parts as bass, harmony, melody, drums/percussion, sfx/upper register twinkle. just five parts, but the bass, harmony, and melody are the most important imo. make sure these parts always sit well with eachother.

also, try not to get too ahead of yourself and overwhelm yourself with a big project. take it one step at a time, and make sure you're having fun with the process most importantly.

>>114544915
I'm not a pro mastering engineer or anything, but I've tried to get decent enough at it. Not that you NEED any of these things for every/any master, but in no particular order:

>Limiters
I like Sonible's smart:Limit a lot. It's really quick to use and it sounds better than other things I've tried. I haven't compared it to Pro L2, but I'm happy enough with it that I'm not curious.

>Color EQs
Tukan EQT-1A is a great free pultec EQ for Reaper (JS plugin). I like it as much as NoiseAsh's Rule Tec, which is also great. I like Acustica's Coral Bax-ter, which is free. Just be sure to gainstage it to around -18 dB at the input.

>Clean EQ
Kirchhoff EQ is similar to Pro-Q3. Worth checking out as an alternative if you don't have either yet. ReEQ (not ReaEQ) is great and free if you use Reaper, but it's not dynamic.

>Compressors
Analog Obsession makes a cool compressor called COMPER. I use it sometimes, and also SPECOMP (spectral compressor). Those are free. Click the logo for oversampling. For paid stuff, Shadow Hills Mastering Compressor Class A is good for color, and TDR Kotelnikov GE is great for cleans. They can be tricky to dial in, though. The regular TDR Kotelnikov is free.

>Weird airwindows stuff
Airwindows "SurgeTide" is cool sometimes for making tracks ebb and flow with the rhythm. Kinda hard to understand and dial in though. Put it after a quicker compressor that handles transients and things. SurgeTide is really slow and basically ignores quick peaks, but it makes your track pulsate in a musically pleasing way. Airwindows "TextureMS" can sound good sometimes IMO. All his stuff is interesting for mixing/mastering if you have time to fall down that rabbit hole. "Airwindows Audiophiles" is a really handy Facebook group, especially if you're autistic.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114548861
>Stereo imaging
I like bx_digital 3 for widening the full frequency spectrum, or Ozone (whatever version) Imager if I just wanna do mids or something. You can also use bx_digital 3 for surgically attenuating problem frequencies, and the dynamic part is okay as a de-esser if you need one.

>Saturation
Sonnox Oxford Inflator is great. There are free alternatives that are very similar.

>Spectral stuff
I like Voxengo TEOTE if I want a spectral balancer. It's kinda like Gulfoss, but with more controls and with a slightly different sound. No psychoacoustic trickery, though, for what it's worth. Soothe 2 is cool sometimes, too (not that it's similar at all).

>Tape
IK Multimedia's Tape Machine 440 sounds nice.

>>114544915
Right now I use mostly Voxengo plugins
>Voxengo TEOTE
Like >>114548874 explained it is similar to Gulfoss. You can change the slope and TEOTE will balance out the sound accordingly, which gives you the control to change the vibe of your sound. You can go darker for example.
>Voxengo Elephant
Probably the best limiter I've ever used. I'm so happy with it I don't even want to try others.
>Voxengo Compressors
People love to talk about compressors and how a couple legendary compressors have some secret sauce processing that no other compressor is able to compete... maybe I'm still an amateur, because I can't hear the "characteristics" between popular compressors. They sound to me pretty much the same if you use similar ones. So I don't worry about "choosing the perfect one" and simply use the ones Voxengo offers me. In mastering it is mostly Polysquasher or Marquis.
>Voxengo EQs
Same as with the compressors, all I need in terms of EQs Voxengo has me covered. For color I use the HarmoniEQ.
>Goodhertz Midside
A simple mid/side plugin for stereo manipulation. It is so simply I get results in a few seconds and never touch it again.
>Sonnox Oxford Inflator
The secret of this plugin is revealed, it is pretty simple processing with a wace shaper that can be copied with free plugins. Look it up on Youtube. But I still prefer the Sonnox Inflator. This is a powerful tool if used correctly. Sometimes I use an Inflator on the mids to get the sound more in your face and another Inflator on the sides with a different setting, depends on the track.
>StandardClip
I use this very subtly on the master to clip the peaks. This makes the compressor and limiter work way better down the signal chain. It also gives you more loudness.

To me they were simply the last great hope of UK rock. The first album rocks like a motherfucker while still having hooks on hooks and continues the great lineage of Kinks - Jam - Blur of snarky realist lyrics. The other records expand the sonic palette (in a period where indie rock either completely forgot about hooks and structure or went completely wimpy), while still keeping their quirky melodic sense, which I still perceive

Btw I like AM, it's overplayed, teen girls masturbated to it ten years ago, idgaf. it's the last rock record that has anything to say about rock and roll and still have cultural relevance and swag too.

The album is a hair-rising fresco of the reality lurking behind the "American dream", and at the same time the chronicle of the narrator's mental breakdown, all drenched in a claustrophobic sense of coming apocalypse. The album opens with one of the weakest songs, the faux-majestic Slaughterhouse, before entering the agon of desperation with the lumbering sermon of Why, over chugging riffs, gothic bass lines and doom-like drumbeats, the archetype for the virulent sonic avalanche of Wicked Puppet Dance, for the manic thrash-inspired rhythmic charge of the deranged and abrasive Tropical Beaches Inc, and for the cinematic The Mask. At the same time, Pamela opts for a simpler and less extreme sound, a noir ballad that transforms into angst-filled kammerspiel.
